      "code": "Better approach: maintain a mapping `val[v]` = current value of v. When we add x, we store x (its current mapped value at insertion time... wait no).\n\nActually: when we add x, the element's \"logical value\" at query time is what matters. We can store the original value added, and at the end, apply the chain of replacements.\n\nBut replacements happen over time. If we add x=1, then do 2 1 2, then add x=1 again, the first 1 becomes 2 but the second 1 also becomes 2 (until further replacements).\n\nKey insight: maintain a union-find or a mapping where `current[v]` = the current value that v maps to. When query \"2 x y\": set `current[x] = current[y]` (because any future lookup of x should give what y currently maps to, but wait - y might change later too).\n\nActually the standard trick: maintain `mapping[v]` where we want to find the \"current\" value of v. When we do \"2 x y\", we want x to become y. But future replacements of y should also affect x.\n\nSo we can use a pointer: `nxt[x] = y`. Then to find the current value of x, follow the chain. But chains can be long.\n\nBetter: `alias[x]` = the value x currently represents. When \"2 x y\": `alias[x] = alias[y]`. But if y changes later, x won't follow.\n\nWe need x to follow y's future changes. So store `alias[x] = y` (not alias[y]), and when looking up, follow the chain with path compression.\n\nWhen \"2 x y\": set `alias[x] = y`. \nTo find current value of x: follow alias chain until we find a fixed point (alias[v] = v).\nUse path compression.\n\nWhen \"1 x\": store x in the array (the original x).\nAt the end: for each stored x, find(x).\n\nBut wait: \"2 x y\" replaces x with y at that point in time. If later \"2 y z\", then x should also become z (since x\u2192y\u2192z). With the alias/find approach this works naturally with path compression.\n\nBut: when we do \"2 x y\", we set alias[x] = y. If x was previously pointed to by something else (say alias[w] = x), then w will now follow x\u2192y which is correct.\n\nLet me verify with example 1:\n- add 3, add 1\n- 2 1 2: alias[1]=2\n- add 2, add 1, add 2\n- 2 1 3: alias[1]=3... but alias[1] was 2, now alias[1]=3? No wait, \"2 1 3\" means replace 1 with 3. But 1 already maps to 2. Hmm.\n\nAfter \"2 1 2\": all 1s become 2. Array is [3,2].\nAfter \"2 1 3\": all 1s become 3. But there are no 1s currently... array has [3,2,2,1,2]. The 1 added after becomes 3.\n\nSo alias[1]=3 (overwrite). find(1)=3. The elements added as 1: first one maps to 3? But expected output shows it's 3 (the first element is 3 which was added as 3, second element added as 1 \u2192 should be 2 after first replacement, then... \n\nWait, \"2 1 3\" replaces current 1s with 3. The element added as 1 (index 1) was already replaced to 2 by \"2 1 2\". So it's now 2, not 3.\n\nThis means the alias approach doesn't work directly because we need to track what value an element had at the time of each replacement.\n\nThe correct approach: store the \"time\" of insertion for each element, and for each replacement query, record it with a timestamp. Then for each element, find the chain of replacements that apply after its insertion time.\n\nThis is more complex. Let me think of the approach with versioned mappings.\n\nFor each value v, maintain a list of (time, new_value) when v was replaced. For an element added at time t with value v, find the replacement of v that happened after t, then follow chains.\n\nimport sys\nfrom sys import stdin\n\ndef main():\n    input = stdin.readline\n    data = sys.stdin.buffer.read().split()\n    idx = 0\n    q = int(data[idx]); idx+=1\n    \n    # For each value, store list of (timestamp, replaced_by)\n    # When \"2 x y\" at time t: replacements[x].append((t, y))\n    # For element added at time t with value v:\n    #   find first replacement of v after time t -> get new value w at time t2\n    #   then find first replacement of w after time t2, etc.\n    \n    from collections import defaultdict\n    import bisect\n    \n    replacements = defaultdict(list)  # v -> sorted list of (time, new_val)\n    repl_times = defaultdict(list)\n    repl_vals = defaultdict(list)\n    \n    elements = []  # (time, value)\n    \n    for t in range(q):\n        tp = data[idx]; idx+=1\n        if tp == b'1':\n            x = int(data[idx]); idx+=1\n            elements.append((t, x))\n        else:\n            x = int(data[idx]); idx+=1\n            y = int(data[idx]); idx+=1\n            repl_times[x].append(t)\n            repl_vals[x].append(y)\n    \n    result = []\n    for (t, v) in elements:\n        cur_v = v\n        cur_t = t\n        while True:\n            times = repl_times[cur_v]\n            if not times:\n                break\n            pos = bisect.bisect_right(times, cur_t)\n            if pos == len(times):\n                break\n            new_t = times[pos]\n            new_v = repl_vals[cur_v][pos]\n            cur_t = new_t\n            cur_v = new_v\n        result.append(cur_v)\n    \n    sys.stdout.write(' '.join(map(str, result)) + '\\n')\n\nmain()",
